          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19754898"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16582901"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the ORAI1 calcium channel. It is located at the cytoplasmic membrane, and is the main channel responsible for the Store Operated Calcium Entry (SOCE) in T cells [3], [4]. It is a redox sensitive protein [2].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1585" y="567" style="redox sensitive"/>
    </node>
    <node id="IP3" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="PLCg"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=CHEBI:16595"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26052328"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23805141"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the second messenger inositol-1,4,5-trisphosphate (IP3), produced by the action of the PLC gamma enzyme. It is an important connection between the TCR signals and the calcium currents [2], [3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1376" y="823" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="IP3R" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IP3 | cROS"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:6180"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26052328"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=30228182"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the inositol trisphosphate receptor (IP3) located at the endoplasmic reticulum membrane. It is a calcium channel opened by the ligation with inositol-1,4,5-trisphosphate (IP3). It induces the depletion of the internal calcium stores [2]. It is a redox sensitive node [3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1500" y="621" style="redox sensitive"/>
    </node>
    <node id="STIM" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="IP3R | cROS"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:11386"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15866891"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16005298"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24053140"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28900911"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the calcium sensor and activator of SOCE STIM1, located at the endoplasmic reticulum. It senses the depletion of the internal calcium reserves and activates ORAI1 [2], [3]. It is also a redox sensitive node [4], [5]. </comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1568" y="676" style="redox sensitive"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CALM" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="cCa"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1442"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19290928"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents calmodulin, a sensor for intracellular calcium [2].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1637" y="1117" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="CALN" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="CALM"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:9315"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1715244"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27941787"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11015619"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the phosphatase calcineurin. This enzyme activates NFAT transcription factor upon elevated cytosolic calcium levels [2], [3], [4].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1254" y="1357" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="RAF" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="RAS"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:9829"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9826444"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14737111"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19542438"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the serine/threonine kinase Raf-1, a MAPKKK upstream of ERK [2], [3], [4].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="996" y="845" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="MEK" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="RAF"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:6847"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19542438"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12899942"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the mitogen-activated protein kinase kinase 7. It is an activator of ERK [2], [3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1018" y="926" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="MAP3K11" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="HPK1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:6850"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10713178"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10849438"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>HGNC:6850
10713178
10849438

This node represents the Mitogen Activated Kinase Kinase Kinase 11, or MLK3. It is an upstream activator of the NFkB and JNK pathways [2], [3].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1357" y="1130" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="MAP2K4" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="MAP3K11 | ASK1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:6844"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29248490"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10785355"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the MKK4, a MAPKK important in the activation of JNK in T cells [2], [3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1399" y="1305" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="MKK3" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="ASK1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:6843"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8974401"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the enzyme MAPKK3, a MAPKK involved in the activation of p38 during intracellular stress [2].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1217" y="1000" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="ASK1" name="MAP3K5" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!cTRX"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:6857"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18206122"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11274345"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17883330"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the Apoptosis signal-regulating kinase 1 (ASK1), a MAPKKK upstream of JNK and P38 which activates in response to cellular stress. It is a redox sensitive node [2], [3], [4].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1227" y="1123" style="redox sensitive"/>
    </node>
    <node id="HPK1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="LAT"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:6863"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10849438"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the hematopoietic progenitor kinase 1 (HPK1), a serine/threonine kinase important for the signaling downstream the TCR [2].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1371" y="905" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="HV1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="cROS"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:28240"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28013412"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23798303"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24890927"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20139987"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25425665"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29643227"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31060879"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the Hv1 proton channel located at the cytoplasmic membrane [3]. This channel extrudes the excess of protons generated by the NADPH-oxidase enzyme, thus preventing cellular acidification [2]. Recent evidences support a role in the modulation of the mROS generation located at the internal mitochondrial membrane [8].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="890" y="847" style="redox sensitive"/>
    </node>
    <node id="mCa" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="cCa:2"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="cCa:1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=CHEBI:29108"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20668216"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=30622345"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29032101"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=30982525"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26100311"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29030115"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represent the mitochondrial level of the Ca ion, an important second messenger for T cells signaling [3]. It is important for the mitochondrial metabolic activity [4], [5], [7]. Recent evidences suggest that the Ca levels are differentially regulated between T cells from neonates and adults [6]. It is a multilevel node.

Level 2 -&gt; very high mCa levels
Level 1 -&gt; intermediate mCa levels
Level 0 -&gt; very low mCa levels</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="781" y="399" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mROS" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="(!(mPRX | mGPX) &amp; (cROS | ETC | mGR | mTR)) | (cROS &amp; (mPRX | mGPX | ETC | mGR | mTR))"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="((!mPRX &amp; mGPX) | (mPRX &amp; !mGPX)) &amp; (ETC | mGR | mTR) &amp; !cROS"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=CHEBI:26523"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23415911"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23880762"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=30466061"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=30057684"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19061483"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27965578"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26100311"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the levels of Reactive Oxigen Species generated in the mitochondria (mROS). This is representing mainly by hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), but it also includes the superoxide anion (O2.-) and other derivatives. It is an important second messenger for signaling but it is detrimental at higher levels. Thus, its concentration is maintained under a strick balance between production and scavenging. It is a multilevel node.

Level 2 --&gt; very high damaging levels of mROS
Level 1 --&gt; normal signaling levels of mROS
Level 0 --&gt; very low levels of mROS
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="601" y="669" style="ROS or ROS source"/>
    </node>
    <node id="mQH2_Q" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="ETC &amp; mdH"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="ETC &amp; !mdH"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=CHEBI:17976"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19061483"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27085844"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CHEBI:17976
19061483
27085844

This node represent the ratio between the reduced (QH2) and the oxidized (Q) ubiquinone, the electron carrier in the mitochondrial internal membrane. At some conditions of very reduced values, it is a source of mROS [2], [3]. It is a multilevel node.

Level 2 --&gt; very reduced
Level 1 --&gt; normal physiological levels
Level 0 --&gt; very oxidized
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="504" y="514" style="ROS or ROS source"/>
    </node>
    <node id="mNADH_NAD" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="(KrebsCycle | mPDH | FAO) &amp; !ETC"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(KrebsCycle | mPDH | FAO) &amp; ETC"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=CHEBI:16908"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28648096"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20175987"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23442855"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19061483"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the ratio between the redox couple of the reduced (NADH) vs oxidized (NAD+) coenzime at the mitochondria. It is an important indicator of the energetic status of the cell [2], [3], [4], [5]. It is a multilevel node.
Level 2 --&gt; corresponds to a very high NADH/NAD+ ratio, the couple is at an extreme of reduction
Level 1 --&gt; corresponds to a hig or medium NADH/NAD+ ratio, the couple is at normal physiological levels of reduction.
Level 0 --&gt; corresponds to a very low NADH/NAD+ ratio, the couple is at an extreme of oxidation.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="352" y="319" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mGSH_GSSG" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="mGR &amp; !mGPX"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="mGR &amp; mGPX"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=CHEBI:16856"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25701705"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28558477"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the ratio between the reduced (GSH) and the oxidized (GSSG) mitochondrial pool of glutathione, an importan antioxidant of the cell [3]. In some cases of reductive stress the extremely reduced GSH/GSSG ratio is an inductor of ROS production by the enzyme Glutathione Reductase [2]. It is a multilevel node.

Level 2 --&gt; highly reduced
Level 1 --&gt; normal physiological reduction status
Level 0 --&gt; highly oxidized
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="96" y="743" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mdH" maxvalue="2">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="ETC &amp; !ATPSyn"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="ETC &amp; ATPSyn"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=CHEBI:24636"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29626541"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19061483"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the proton concentration at the mitochondrial intermediate membrane space. It is the proton motive force which drive ATP production by the ATP synthase. Several evidences connect the proton motive force to the gereation on mROS [2], [3]. It is a multilevel node.

Level 2 --&gt; very high proton motive force
Level 1 --&gt; intermediate levels of proton motive force
Level 0 --&gt; very low proton motive force</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="57" y="519" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mNADPH_NADP" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="(mNNT:2 &amp; !mIDH2) | (mNNT:2 &amp; mIDH2) | (mNNT:1 &amp; mIDH2)"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(!mNNT &amp; mIDH2) | (mNNT:1 &amp; !mIDH2)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=CHEBI:16474"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28648096"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20175987"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23442855"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the ratio between the redox couple of the reduced (NADHP) vs oxidized (NADP+) coenzime in the mitochondria. It is an important indicator of the reducing power of the cell [2], [3], [4]. It is a multilevel node.
Level 2 --&gt; corresponds to a very high NADPH/NADP+ ratio, the couple is at an extreme of reduction
Level 1 --&gt; corresponds to a hig or medium NADPH/NADP+ ratio, the couple is at normal physiological levels of reduction.
Level 0 --&gt; corresponds to a very low NADPH/NADP+ ratio, the couple is at an extreme of oxidation.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="452" y="929" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mNNT" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="(mNADH_NAD:2 &amp; mdH:2) | (mNADH_NAD:1 &amp; mdH:2) | (mNADH_NAD:2 &amp; mdH:1)"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="mNADH_NAD:1 &amp; mdH:1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:7863"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28648096"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16730324"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20007326"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the NAM nucleotide transhydrogenase, an important mediator of the conversion between NADH and NADPH pools in the mitochondria . It is regulated by the proton motive force. It is a multilevel node.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="12" y="801" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mIDH2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="KrebsCycle"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:5383"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28648096"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20007326"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the mitochondrial enzyme Isocitrate dehydrogenase II. It is a source of mitochondrial NADPH [2], [3].  </comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="227" y="638" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mGPX" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="mGSH_GSSG:2 &amp; !mROS"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="mGSH_GSSG:1 &amp; !mROS"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:4553"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23397885"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the mitochondrial levels of the glutathione peroxidase. It is an important element of the antioxidant machinery [2]. It is a multilevel node.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="448" y="1256" style="redox sensitive"/>
    </node>
    <node id="mGR" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="mGSH_GSSG:2 &amp; (mNADPH_NADP:1 | mNADPH_NADP:2)"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(mNADPH_NADP:1 &amp; !mGSH_GSSG) | (mNADPH_NADP:1 &amp; mGSH_GSSG:1) | (mNADPH_NADP:2 &amp; !mGSH_GSSG) | (mNADPH_NADP:2 &amp; mGSH_GSSG:1)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:4623"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25701705"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node repesents the mitochondrial enzyme Glutathione Reductase (mGR). This enzyme is important in the generation of reduced Glutathione from NADPH. It is a source of ROS at extreme reduction conditions. It is a multilevel node [2].

Level 2 --&gt; highly reduced enzyme
Level 1 --&gt; normal physiological redox status of the enzyme
Level 0 --&gt; highly oxidized enzyme
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="444" y="1040" style="ROS or ROS source"/>
    </node>
    <node id="mPDHP" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="mCa &amp; !mNADH_NAD"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:9279"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=30982525"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the enzyme Pyruvate Dehydrogenase Phosphatase located at the mitochondria. This enzyme is a positive regulator of the Pyruvate Dehydrogenase. It is an important mediator of the oxidative metabolism in the mitochondria [2].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="799" y="565" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mTR" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="mTRX:2 &amp; mNADPH_NADP:2"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(mNADPH_NADP:1 &amp; !mTRX) | (mNADPH_NADP:1 &amp; mTRX:1) | (mNADPH_NADP:2 &amp; !mTRX) | (mNADPH_NADP:2 &amp; mTRX:1) | (mNADPH_NADP:1 &amp; mTRX:2)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:18155"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29278740"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25701705"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20175987"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node repesents the mitochondrial enzyme Thioredoxin Reductase (mTR) [2]. This enzyme is important in the generation of reduced Thioredoxin from NADPH. It is a source of ROS at extreme reduction conditions [3], [4]. It is a multilevel node.

Level 2 --&gt; highly reduced enzyme
Level 1 --&gt; normal physiological redox status of the enzyme
Level 0 --&gt; highly oxidized enzyme
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="652" y="1254" style="ROS or ROS source"/>
    </node>
    <node id="mTRX" maxvalue="2">
      <value val="2">
        <exp str="mTR &amp; !mROS"/>
      </value>
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="mTR &amp; mROS:1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:17772"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23397885"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25701705"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>HGNC:17772
This node represents the thioredoxin mitochondrial pool. This is an important element on the antioxidant machinery of the cell. It receives electrons from NADPH and transfers the electrons to other signaling proteins [2]. In some cases of reductive stress the extremely reduced TRX pool is an inductor of ROS production by the enzyme Thioredoxin Reductase [3]. It is a multilevel node.

Level 2 --&gt; highly reduced
Level 1 --&gt; normal physiological reduction status
Level 0 --&gt; highly oxidized</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="202" y="1320" style="redox sensitive"/>
    </node>
    <node id="mPRX" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(mTRX &amp; !mROS) | (mTRX:2 &amp; mROS)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:9354"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23397885"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>HGNC:9354
23397885

This node represents the mitochondrial pool of peroxiredoxin. It is an important antioxidant protein also involved in redox signaling [2].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="577" y="601" style="redox sensitive"/>
    </node>
    <node id="mShuttle" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="mIDH2 &amp; mNADPH_NADP"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:10979"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28648096"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20007326"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the 2-oxoglutarate/isocitrate NADP(H)-redox shuttle located in the mitochondria. It connects the mitochondrial and cytosolic NADPH pools [2], [3]. </comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="441" y="867" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mPDH" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(mPDHP | PYR) &amp; !mPDHK &amp; !mNADH_NAD"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:8806"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=30982525"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the Pyruvate Dehydrogenase enzyme, located in the mitochondria. This enzyme is important for the complete oxidation of glucose derivatives [2]. </comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="416" y="752" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mPDHK" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!mNADH_NAD &amp; HIF1A"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:8809"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16517405"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25437876"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>This node represents the enzyme Pyruvate Dehydrogenase Kinase located at the mitochondria. This enzyme is a negative regulator of the Pyruvate Dehydrogenase. It is an important mediator of the metabolic shift towards aerobic glycolysis [2], [3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="277" y="753" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="mATP_ADP" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="ATPSyn"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
